{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475820"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:38:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:38:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12820"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12820"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.47,0.11,0.06,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5263"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48679"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5263"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12820"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33624"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"754"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2647"},{"type":"tags","id":"3764"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11093"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44139"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48679"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy is brought by his parents to the General Practice clinic with difficulty walking, fatigue, and pain in his bones, particularly in his legs and arms. The family are recently arrived refugees from Sudan. On examination, the child\u0027s height and weight are below average for his age. His legs and arms appear to be bowed. His joints are swollen, and his muscles seem weak. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn investigation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003Eserum calcium 1.8 mmol/L (2.1-2.6)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Eserum phosphorus 0.69 mmol/L (0.81-1.78)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ealkaline phosphatase 530 U/L (100-420)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome X-rays are to be arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following radiological findings is most likely to be associated with this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subchondral sclerosis","Metaphyseal splaying","Looser\u0027s zones","Popcorn calcification","Subperiosteal bone resorption"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of this five-year-old boy is consistent with rickets, a condition that leads to impaired bone growth and development. Vitamin D deficiency is by far the most common cause of nutritional rickets. Rarely, nutritional deficiency of calcium or phosphorus can result in rickets. Other less frequent causes include genetic causes, drug-induced rickets, and rickets secondary to liver diseases. The spectrum of presentation varies from being asymptomatic to irritability, growth retardation and sudden death. The prevalence of rickets is higher in developing counties than in developed countries. It is particularly common in regions where the diet is poor and largely dependent on vegetables, with little meat. Limited exposure to sunlight is another important cause, particularly in regions where cultural practices restrict access to the sun.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe radiological finding most likely to be associated with rickets is \u003Cstrong\u003Emetaphyseal splaying\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a characteristic finding on X-ray in children with rickets, where the metaphysis of the long bones appears flared and widened as they are affected by the lack of mineralisation. Other radiographic findings in rickets may include cupping and fraying of the metaphysis, osteopaenia, and generalised demineralisation of the bones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubchondral sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to thickening and hardening of bone underneath cartilage in a joint which can be seen on X-ray. While subchondral sclerosis can be seen in some bone disorders, it is not typically associated with rickets. Rather, subchondral sclerosis is a radiographic finding that is more commonly associated with osteoarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELooser\u0027s zones\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as pseudo fractures, cortical infractions or Milkman lines are radiolucent lines seen in the cortex of long bones on X-ray. They are typically seen in patients with osteomalacia, a condition characterised by impaired mineralisation of bone due to a deficiency in vitamin D. While Looser\u0027s zones can be seen in severe rickets, they are not as characteristic or common as metaphyseal changes. In rickets, metaphyseal splaying, cupping, and fraying are the more typical and earlier radiographic findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPopcorn calcification\u003C/strong\u003E refers to amorphous calcifications often with rings and arcs that resemble popped corn kernels. This type of calcification may be seen in many radiological settings including chondroid lesions and fibrous dysplasia. Popcorn calcification is not typically associated with rickets, which is a metabolic bone disorder that affects bone mineralisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubperiosteal bone resorption\u003C/strong\u003E is bone destruction below the periosteum secondary to osteoclastic activity, resulting in an irregular, lace-like cortical appearance. This is a radiographic finding seen in a variety of conditions, including hyperparathyroidism, osteitis deformans (Paget\u0027s disease), and osteomalacia. This finding is not typically associated with rickets, which is characterised by weakened bones with decreased mineralisation, rather than cortical bone loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The radiological finding most likely to be associated with rickets is metaphyseal splaying, cupping and fraying.","Looser\u0027s zones can be seen in severe rickets, though metaphyseal changes are more characteristic."],"references":["Shore RM, Chesney RW. Rickets: Part I. (2013) Pediatric radiology. 43 (2): 140-51.","Dahash BA, Sankararaman S. Rickets. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33624"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12820"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33624"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-15T19:13:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-15T19:14:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5263"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48679"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"descriptio